data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, was false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use IsTrue with LINQ, but prefer CollectionAssert when possible
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | You already check for 3, so `> 0` is redundant |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(a)` | Clearer failure message |
| `users.Single(...)` | `users.SingleOrDefault(...)` | `Single` throws `InvalidOperationException` before your assert runs, giving a confusing failure |
| bare `Assert.IsTrue(...)` | Add a `message` parameter | E.g. `"Expected all users to be active"` |

**Also available — `CollectionAssert`:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.AllMatch(users, u => u.IsActive);      // MSTest 3.x+
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);             // order matters
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);        // order ignored
```

If you're on **MSTest v3+**, `CollectionAssert.AllMatch` replaces the LINQ `All()` pattern. For older versions, `Assert.IsTrue` with a message string is the standard approach.
